    },
    {
      "id": 2,
      "text": "A 1774 milestone on Middle Country Road, one of only three still standing, marks Coram’s early settlement history.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        1
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Web source 1"
      ],
      "source": "https://www.coramcivic.org/history-of-coram/"
    },
    {
      "id": 3,
      "text": "From 1784 to 1885, Coram hosted Brookhaven’s town meetings in the Davis Town Meeting House.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        17
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coram%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 4,
      "text": "During the Revolution, Benjamin Tallmadge and 12 Culper Ring men burned 300 tons of British hay in Coram, earning Washington’s praise.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        12,
        13,
        14,
        15
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coram%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 5,
      "text": "Coram commemorates that hay‑burning victory each October with an annual celebration.",
      "sourceSentenceIds": [
        16
      ],
      "sourceLabels": [
        "Wikipedia"
      ],
      "source": "https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Coram%2C_New_York"
    },
    {
      "id": 6,
      "text": "Coram’s name may stem from the Native American “Wincoram” noted in 1703 records.",
